Suppose you own [`x`] fezzes and [`y`] bow ties. Of course, [`x`] and [`y`] are both greater than 1.
a.  How many combinations of fez and bow tie can you make? You can wear only one fez and one bow tie at a time. Explain.

a.  Explain why the answer is _also_ [`{x+y \choose 2} - {x \choose 2} - {y \choose 2}\text{.}`] (If this is what you claimed the answer was in part (a), try it again.)

a.  Use your answers to parts (a) and (b) to give a combinatorial proof of the identity

    [```
                {x+y \choose 2} - {x \choose 2} - {y \choose 2} = xy.
              ```]

